# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: docsis-cable
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:docsis-cable/cable-modem-termination-system] A **cable modem termination system** (**CMTS**, also called a **CMTS Edge Router**) is a piece of equipment, typically located in a cable company's headend or hubsite, which is used to provide data services, such as cable Internet or Voice over IP, to cable subscribers.
[src:docsis-cable/cable-modem-termination-system] A CMTS provides similar functions to a DSLAM in a digital subscriber line or an optical line termination in a passive optical network.
[src:docsis-cable/cable-modem-termination-system] In order to provide high speed data services, a cable company will connect its headend to the Internet via very high capacity data links to a network service provider.
[src:docsis-cable/cable-modem-termination-system] On the subscriber side of the headend, the CMTS enables communication with subscribers' cable modems.
[src:docsis-cable/cable-modem-termination-system] A given headend may have between 1–12 CMTSs to service the cable modem population served by that headend or HFC hub.
[src:docsis-cable/cable-modem-termination-system] One way to think of a CMTS is to imagine a router with Ethernet interfaces (connections) on one side and coaxial cable RF interfaces on the other side.
[src:docsis-cable/cable-modem-termination-system] The Ethernet side is known as the Network Side Interface or NSI.
[src:docsis-cable/cable-modem-termination-system] A service group is a group of customers that share communication RF channels and thus bandwidth.
[src:docsis-cable/cable-modem-termination-system] A CMTS has separate RF interfaces and connectors for downlink and uplink signals.
[src:docsis-cable/cable-modem-termination-system] The RF/coax interfaces carry RF signals to and from coaxial "trunks" connected to subscribers' cable modems, using one pair of connectors per trunk, one for downlink and the other for uplink.
[src:docsis-cable/cable-modem-termination-system] In other words, there can be a pair of RF connectors for every service group, although it is possible to configure a network with different numbers of connectors that service a set of service groups, based on the number of downstream and upstream channels the cable modems in every service group use.
[src:docsis-cable/cable-modem-termination-system] Every connector has a finite number of channels it can carry, such as 16 channels per downstream connector, and 4 channels per upstream connector, depending on the CMTS.
[src:docsis-cable/cable-modem-termination-system] For example, if the cable modems on every service group use 24 channels for downstream, and 2 channels for upstream, then 3 downstream connectors can service the cable modems on two service groups, and be serviced by 1 upstream connector.
[src:docsis-cable/cable-modem-termination-system] A service group may serve up to 500 households.
[src:docsis-cable/cable-modem-termination-system] A service group has channels, whose bandwidth is shared among all members of the service group.
[src:docsis-cable/cable-modem-termination-system] The channels are later regrouped at the cable headend or distribution hub and serviced by CMTSs and other equipment such as Edge QAMs.
[src:docsis-cable/cable-modem-termination-system] Examples of optics platforms are the Arris CH3000 and Cisco Prisma II.
[src:docsis-cable/cable-modem-termination-system] At the other end of the network, an optical node converts the light pulses into RF signals again and sends them through a coaxial cable "trunk".
[src:docsis-cable/cable-modem-termination-system] The trunk has one or more amplifiers along its length, and on the trunk there are distribution "taps" to which customers' modems are connected via coaxial cable.
[src:docsis-cable/cable-modem-termination-system] In fact, most CMTSs have both Ethernet interfaces (or other more traditional high-speed data interfaces like SONET) as well as RF interfaces.
[src:docsis-cable/cable-modem-termination-system] In this way, traffic that is coming from the Internet can be routed (or bridged) through the Ethernet interface, through the CMTS and then onto the RF interfaces that are connected to the cable company's **hybrid fiber coax** (HFC).
[src:docsis-cable/cable-modem-termination-system] The traffic winds its way through the HFC to end up at the cable modem in the subscriber's home.
[src:docsis-cable/cable-modem-termination-system] Traffic from a subscriber's home system goes through the cable modem and out to the Internet in the opposite direction.
[src:docsis-cable/cable-modem-termination-system] Traffic destined for the cable modem from the Internet, known as downstream traffic, is carried in IP packets encapsulated according to DOCSIS standard.
[src:docsis-cable/cable-modem-termination-system] These packets are carried on data streams that are typically modulated onto a TV channel using either 64-QAM or 256-QAM versions of quadrature amplitude modulation.
[src:docsis-cable/cable-modem-termination-system] Upstream data (data from cable modems to the headend or Internet) is carried in Ethernet frames encapsulated inside DOCSIS frames modulated with QPSK, 16-QAM, 32-QAM, 64-QAM or 128-QAM using TDMA, ATDMA or S-CDMA frequency sharing mechanisms.
[src:docsis-cable/cable-modem-termination-system] This is usually done at the "subband" or "return" portion of the cable TV spectrum (also known as the "T" channels), a much lower part of the frequency spectrum than the downstream signal, usually 5–42 MHz in DOCSIS 2.0 or 5–65 MHz in EuroDOCSIS.
[src:docsis-cable/cable-modem-termination-system] A typical CMTS allows a subscriber's computer to obtain an IP address by forwarding DHCP requests to the relevant servers.
[src:docsis-cable/cable-modem-termination-system] This DHCP server returns, for the most part, what looks like a typical response including an assigned IP address for the computer, gateway/router addresses to use, DNS servers, etc.
[src:docsis-cable/cable-modem-termination-system] The CMTS may also implement some basic filtering to protect against unauthorized users and various attacks.
[src:docsis-cable/cable-modem-termination-system] Traffic shaping is sometimes performed to prioritize application traffic, perhaps based upon subscribed plan or download usage and also to provide guaranteed Quality of service (QoS) for the cable operator's own PacketCable-based VOIP service.
[src:docsis-cable/cable-modem-termination-system] However, the function of traffic shaping is more likely done by a Cable Modem or policy traffic switch.
[src:docsis-cable/cable-modem-termination-system] A CMTS may also act as a bridge or router.
[src:docsis-cable/cable-modem-termination-system] A customer's cable modem cannot communicate directly with other modems on the line.
[src:docsis-cable/cable-modem-termination-system] In general, cable modem traffic is routed to other cable modems or to the Internet through a series of CMTSs and traditional routers.
[src:docsis-cable/cable-modem-termination-system] However, a route could conceivably pass through a single CMTS.
[src:docsis-cable/cable-modem-termination-system] A **CCAP** (Converged Cable Access Platform) combines CMTS and Edge QAM functionality in a single device so that it can provide both data (internet) with CMTS functionality, and video (TV channels) with Edge QAM functionality.
[src:docsis-cable/cable-modem-termination-system] Edge QAM (Quadrature Amplitude Modulator/Modulation) converts video sent via IP (internet protocol) or otherwise, into a QAM signal for delivery over a cable network.
[src:docsis-cable/cable-modem-termination-system] Edge QAMs are normally standalone devices placed at the "edge" of a network.
[src:docsis-cable/cable-modem-termination-system] They can also be connected to a CMTS core, to make up an M-CMTS system which is more scalable.
[src:docsis-cable/cable-modem-termination-system] A CMTS core is normally a conventional or I-CMTS that supports operation as a CMTS core in an M-CMTS system.
[src:docsis-cable/cable-modem-termination-system] A CMTS can be broken down into several different architectures, Integrated CMTS (I-CMTS), Modular (M-CMTS), Virtual CMTS (vCMTS) and remote CMTS.
[src:docsis-cable/cable-modem-termination-system] An I-CMTS incorporates into a single unit all components necessary for its operation.
[src:docsis-cable/cable-modem-termination-system] There are both pros and cons to each type of architecture.
[src:docsis-cable/cable-modem-termination-system] In a M-CMTS solution the architecture of an I-CMTS is broken up into two components.
[src:docsis-cable/cable-modem-termination-system] The first part is the Physical Downstream component (PHY) which is known as the Edge QAM (EQAM).
[src:docsis-cable/cable-modem-termination-system] The second part is the IP networking and DOCSIS MAC Component which is referred to as the M-CMTS Core.
[src:docsis-cable/cable-modem-termination-system] There are also several new protocols and components introduced with this type of architecture.
[src:docsis-cable/cable-modem-termination-system] One is the DOCSIS Timing Interface, which provides a reference frequency between the EQAM and M-CMTS Core via a DTI Server.
[src:docsis-cable/cable-modem-termination-system] The second is the Downstream External PHY Interface (DEPI).
[src:docsis-cable/cable-modem-termination-system] The DEPI protocol controls the delivery of DOCSIS frames from the M-CMTS Core to the EQAM devices Some of the challenges that entail an M-CMTS platform are increased complexity in RF combining and an increase in the number of failure points.
[src:docsis-cable/cable-modem-termination-system] One of the benefits of an M-CMTS architecture is that it is extremely scalable to larger numbers of downstream channels.
[src:docsis-cable/cable-modem-termination-system] Virtual CCAPs (vCCAPs) or virtual CMTSs (vCMTSs) are implemented on commercial off the shelf x86-based servers with specialized software, and can be used to increase service capacity without purchasing new CMTS/CCAP chassis, or add features to the CMTS/CCAP more quickly.
[src:docsis-cable/cable-modem-termination-system] Remote CMTS/Remote CCAP moves all CMTS/CCAP functionality to the outside plant, in stark contrast to conventional CMTSs or CCAPs which are installed at a service provider location.
[src:docsis-cable/cable-modem] A **cable modem** is a type of network bridge or gateway that provides bi-directional data communication via radio frequency channels on a hybrid fiber-coaxial, radio frequency over glass and coaxial cable infrastructure.
[src:docsis-cable/cable-modem] Cable modems are primarily used to deliver broadband Internet access in the form of cable Internet.
[src:docsis-cable/cable-modem] They are commonly deployed in the Americas, Asia, Australia, and Europe.
[src:docsis-cable/cable-modem] Internet Experiment Note (IEN) 96 (1979) describes an early RF cable modem system.
[src:docsis-cable/cable-modem] The IEEE 802 Committee defined 10BROAD36 in 802.3b-1985 as a 10 Mbit/s IEEE 802.3 broadband system to run up to 3,600 metres (11,800 ft) over CATV coax network cabling.
[src:docsis-cable/cable-modem] The word *broadband* as used in the original IEEE 802.3 specifications implied operation in frequency-division multiplexed (FDM) channel bands as opposed to digital baseband modulation (also known as line coding), which begins near zero Hz and extends upward.
[src:docsis-cable/cable-modem] 10BROAD36 equipment was not developed by many vendors nor deployed in many user networks as compared to equipment for baseband Ethernet standards such as 10BASE5 (1983), 10BASE2 (1985), 10BASE-T (1990), etc.
[src:docsis-cable/cable-modem] The IEEE 802 Committee also specified a broadband CATV digital networking standard in 1989 with 802.7-1989.
[src:docsis-cable/cable-modem] However, like 10BROAD36, 802.7-1989 saw little commercial success.
[src:docsis-cable/cable-modem] Hybrid Networks developed, demonstrated and patented the first high-speed, asymmetrical cable modem system in 1990.
[src:docsis-cable/cable-modem] A key Hybrid Networks insight was that in the nascent days of the Internet, data downloading constituted the majority of the data traffic, and this could be served adequately with a highly asymmetrical data network (i.e., a large downstream data pipe and many small upstream data pipes).
[src:docsis-cable/cable-modem] This allowed CATV operators to offer high-speed data services immediately without first requiring an expensive system upgrade.
[src:docsis-cable/cable-modem] Also key was that it saw that the upstream and downstream communications could be on the same or different communications media using different protocols respectively working in each direction to establish a closed-loop communications system.
[src:docsis-cable/cable-modem] The speeds and protocols used in each direction would be very different.
[src:docsis-cable/cable-modem] The earliest systems used the public switched telephone network (PSTN) for the return path since very few cable systems were bi-directional.
[src:docsis-cable/cable-modem] Later systems used CATV for the upstream as well as the downstream path.
[src:docsis-cable/cable-modem] Hybrid's system architecture is used for most cable modem systems today.
[src:docsis-cable/cable-modem] LANcity was an early pioneer in cable modems, developing a proprietary system that was widely deployed in the U.S.
[src:docsis-cable/cable-modem] LANcity, which was led by the Iranian-American engineer Rouzbeh Yassini, was then acquired by Bay Networks.
[src:docsis-cable/cable-modem] Bay Networks was subsequently acquired by Nortel.
[src:docsis-cable/cable-modem] Nortel at the time had formed a joint-venture with Antec called ARRIS Interactive.
[src:docsis-cable/cable-modem] Because of contractual agreements with Antec involving this joint venture, Nortel spun the LANCity group out into the ARRIS Interactive joint-venture.
[src:docsis-cable/cable-modem] ARRIS continues to make cable modems and cable modem termination system (CMTS) equipment compliant with the DOCSIS standard.
[src:docsis-cable/cable-modem] Zenith offered a cable modem technology using its own protocol which it introduced in 1993, being one of the first cable modem providers.
[src:docsis-cable/cable-modem] Zenith Homeworks used BPSK (Bi-Phase Shift Keyed) modulation to achieve 500 Kbit/sec in 600 kHz, or 4 Mbit/sec in 6 MHz.
[src:docsis-cable/cable-modem] Com21 was another early pioneer in cable modems, and quite successful until proprietary systems were made obsolete by the DOCSIS standardization.
[src:docsis-cable/cable-modem] The Com21 system used a *ComController* as the central bridge in CATV network head-ends, the ComPort cable modem in various models and the NMAPS management system using HP OpenView as the platform.
[src:docsis-cable/cable-modem] Later they also introduced a return path multiplexer to overcome noise problems when combining return path signals from multiple areas.
[src:docsis-cable/cable-modem] The proprietary protocol was based on Asynchronous Transfer Mode (ATM).
[src:docsis-cable/cable-modem] The central ComController switch was a modular system offering one downstream channel (transmitter) and one management module.
[src:docsis-cable/cable-modem] The remaining slots could be used for upstream receivers (2 per card), dual Ethernet 10BaseT and later also Fast Ethernet and ATM interfaces.
[src:docsis-cable/cable-modem] The ATM interface became the most popular, as it supported the increasing bandwidth demands and also supported VLANs.
[src:docsis-cable/cable-modem] Com21 developed a DOCSIS modem, but the company filed for bankruptcy in 2003 and closed.
[src:docsis-cable/cable-modem] The DOCSIS CMTS assets of COM21 were acquired by ARRIS.
[src:docsis-cable/cable-modem] CDLP was a proprietary system manufactured by Motorola.
[src:docsis-cable/cable-modem] CDLP customer premises equipment (CPE) was capable of both PSTN (telephone network) and radio frequency (cable) return paths.
[src:docsis-cable/cable-modem] The standard is in little use now as new providers use, and existing providers having changed to, the DOCSIS standard.
[src:docsis-cable/cable-modem] The Motorola CDLP proprietary CyberSURFR is an example of a device that was built to the CDLP standard, capable of a peak 10 Mbit/s downstream and 1.532 Mbit/s upstream.
[src:docsis-cable/cable-modem] CDLP supported a maximum downstream bandwidth of 30 Mbit/s which could be reached by using several cable modems.
[src:docsis-cable/cable-modem] The Australian ISP BigPond employed this system when it started cable modem tests in 1996.
[src:docsis-cable/cable-modem] For a number of years cable Internet access was only available in Sydney, Melbourne and Brisbane via CDLP.
[src:docsis-cable/cable-modem] This network ran parallel to the newer DOCSIS system for several years.
[src:docsis-cable/cable-modem] In 2004, the CDLP network was terminated and replaced by DOCSIS.
[src:docsis-cable/cable-modem] CDLP has also been rolled out at the French cable operator Numericable before upgrading its IP broadband network using DOCSIS.
[src:docsis-cable/cable-modem] Digital Video Broadcasting (DVB) and Digital Audio Visual Council (DAVIC) are European-formed organizations that developed some cable modem standards.
[src:docsis-cable/cable-modem] However, these standards have not been as widely adopted as DOCSIS.
[src:docsis-cable/cable-modem] In the mid-1990s the IEEE 802 committee formed a subcommittee (802.14) to develop a standard for cable modem systems.
[src:docsis-cable/cable-modem] IEEE 802.14 developed a draft standard, which was ATM-based.
[src:docsis-cable/cable-modem] However, the 802.14 working group was disbanded when North American multi system operators (MSOs) instead backed the then-fledgling DOCSIS 1.0 specification, which generally used best-effort service and was IP-based (with extension codepoints to support ATM for QoS in the future).
[src:docsis-cable/cable-modem] MSOs were interested in quickly deploying service to compete for broadband Internet access customers instead of waiting on the slower, iterative, and deliberative processes of standards development committees.
[src:docsis-cable/cable-modem] Azzam was Secretary of the IEEE 802.14 Working Group, and his book, *High-Speed Cable Modems*, describes many of the proposals submitted to 802.14.
[src:docsis-cable/cable-modem] Although the Internet Engineering Task Force (IETF) generally does not generate complete cable modem standards, the IETF chartered Working Groups (WGs) that produced various standards related to cable modem technologies (including 802.14, DOCSIS, PacketCable, and others).
[src:docsis-cable/cable-modem] In the late 1990s, a consortium of US cable operators, known as "MCNS" formed to quickly develop an open and interoperable cable modem specification.
[src:docsis-cable/cable-modem] The group essentially combined technologies from the two dominant proprietary systems at the time, taking the physical layer from the Motorola CDLP system and the MAC layer from the LANcity system.
[src:docsis-cable/cable-modem] While deployed DOCSIS RFI 1.0 equipment generally only supported best-effort service, the DOCSIS RFI 1.0 Interim-01 document discussed quality of service (QoS) extensions and mechanisms using IntServ, RSVP, RTP, and Synchronous Transfer Mode (STM) telephony (as opposed to ATM).
[src:docsis-cable/cable-modem] DOCSIS RFI 1.1 later added more robust and standardized QoS mechanisms to DOCSIS.
[src:docsis-cable/cable-modem] DOCSIS 2.0 added support for S-CDMA PHY, while DOCSIS 3.0 added IPv6 support and channel bonding to allow a single cable modem to use concurrently more than one upstream channel and more than one downstream channel in parallel.
[src:docsis-cable/cable-modem] Virtually all cable modems operating in the field today are compliant with one of the DOCSIS versions.
[src:docsis-cable/cable-modem] Because of the differences in the European PAL and US's NTSC systems two main versions of DOCSIS exist, DOCSIS and EuroDOCSIS.
[src:docsis-cable/cable-modem] The main differences are found in the width of RF-channels: 6 MHz for the US and 8 MHz for Europe.
[src:docsis-cable/cable-modem] A third variant of DOCSIS was developed in Japan and has seen limited deployment in that country.
[src:docsis-cable/cable-modem] In 2004, the Multimedia over Coax Alliance (MoCA) was established to develop industry standards for the connected home using the existing coaxial cabling.
[src:docsis-cable/cable-modem] Initially developed for in-home networking with MoCA 1.0/1.1, the MoCA standards have continued to develop with MoCA 2.0/2.1 in 2010 and MoCa 2.5 in 2016.
[src:docsis-cable/cable-modem] In 2017, Multimedia over Coax Alliance introduced MoCA Access specification, based on the MoCA 2.5 standard, suitable for addressing broadband network access in-building using coaxial cabling.
[src:docsis-cable/cable-modem] With the development of voice over Internet Protocol (VoIP) telephony, analog telephone adapters (ATA) have been incorporated into many cable modems for providing telephone service.
[src:docsis-cable/cable-modem] An embedded ATA is known as an *embedded multimedia terminal adapter* (E-MTA).
[src:docsis-cable/cable-modem] Many cable TV service providers also offer VoIP-based telephone service via the cable infrastructure (PacketCable).
[src:docsis-cable/cable-modem] Some high-speed Internet customers may use VoIP telephony by subscribing to a third-party service, such as Vonage, MagicJack+ and NetTALK.
[src:docsis-cable/cable-modem] In network topology, a cable modem is a network bridge that conforms to IEEE 802.1D for Ethernet networking (with some modifications).
[src:docsis-cable/cable-modem] The cable modem bridges Ethernet frames between a customer LAN and the coax network.
[src:docsis-cable/cable-modem] Technically, it is a modem because it must modulate data to transmit it over the cable network, and it must demodulate data from the cable network to receive it.
[src:docsis-cable/cable-modem] It implements an Ethernet PHY on its LAN interface, and a DOCSIS-defined cable-specific PHY on its HFC cable interface.
[src:docsis-cable/cable-modem] The term *cable modem* refers to this cable-specific PHY.
[src:docsis-cable/cable-modem] The Network Layer is implemented as an IP host in that it has its own IP address used by the network operator to maintain the device.
[src:docsis-cable/cable-modem] In the transport layer the cable modem supports UDP in association with its own IP address, and it supports filtering based on TCP and UDP port numbers to, for example, block forwarding of NetBIOS traffic out of the customer's LAN.
[src:docsis-cable/cable-modem] In the Application Layer, the cable modem supports certain protocols that are used for management and maintenance, notably Dynamic Host Configuration Protocol (DHCP), SNMP, and TFTP.
[src:docsis-cable/cable-modem] Some cable modems may incorporate a router and a DHCP server to provide the LAN with IP network addressing.
[src:docsis-cable/cable-modem] From a data forwarding and network topology perspective, this router functionality is typically kept distinct from the cable modem functionality (at least logically) even though the two may share a single enclosure and appear as one unit, sometimes called a residential gateway.
[src:docsis-cable/cable-modem] So, the cable modem function will have its own IP address and MAC address as will the router.
[src:docsis-cable/cable-modem] Cable modems can have a problem known in industry jargon as "flap" or "flapping".
[src:docsis-cable/cable-modem] A modem flap is when the connection by the modem to the head-end has been dropped (gone offline) and then comes back online.
[src:docsis-cable/cable-modem] The time offline or rate of flap is not typically recorded, only the incidence.
[src:docsis-cable/cable-modem] While this is a common occurrence and usually unnoticed, if a modem's flap is extremely high, these disconnects can cause service to be disrupted.
[src:docsis-cable/cable-modem] If there are usability problems due to flap the typical cause is a defective modem or very high amounts of traffic on the service provider's network (upstream utilization too high).
[src:docsis-cable/cable-modem] Types of flap include reinsertions, hits and misses, and power adjustments.
[src:docsis-cable/cable-modem] In January 2020, a vulnerability affecting cable modems using Broadcom chipsets was disclosed and named Cable Haunt.
[src:docsis-cable/cable-modem] Security researchers say that the vulnerability affects hundreds of millions of devices.
[src:docsis-cable/cable-modem] Exploits are possible because of the use of default credentials in the spectrum analyzer component of the modem (mostly used for debugging purposes) accessible through a network port which is open by default in the vulnerable models.
[src:docsis-cable/docsis] DOCSIS was originally developed by CableLabs and contributing companies, including Broadcom, Comcast, Cox, General Instrument, Motorola, Terayon, and Time Warner Cable.
[src:docsis-cable/docsis] (QoS) mechanisms that were outlined in DOCSIS 1.0.
[src:docsis-cable/docsis] Released in December 2001, DOCSIS 2.0 enhanced upstream data rates in response to increased demand for symmetric services such as IP telephony.
[src:docsis-cable/docsis] inside a block spectrum that could end up being about 200 MHz wide.
[src:docsis-cable/docsis] , broadband provider Comcast announced in February 2016 that several cities within its footprint will have DOCSIS 3.1 availability before the end of the year.
[src:docsis-cable/docsis] announced it would become the first major U.S. cable company to fully transition to the DOCSIS 3.1 platform.
[src:docsis-cable/docsis] Improves DOCSIS 3.1 to use the full spectrum of the cable plant (0 MHz to ~1.8 GHz) at the same time in both upstream and downstream directions.
[src:docsis-cable/docsis] CableLabs released the full specification in October 2017.
[src:docsis-cable/docsis] Previously branded as DOCSIS 3.1 Full Duplex, these technologies have been rebranded as part of DOCSIS 4.0.
[src:docsis-cable/docsis] There is currently no official version of DOCSIS declared as DOCSIS 5.0 by CableLabs.
[src:docsis-cable/docsis] There is speculation proposing targets of 25 Gbit/s downstream and at least 5 Gbit/s upstream at 3 GHz, and a reference implementation that was demonstrated in 2024.
[src:docsis-cable/docsis] Several DOCSIS versions can co exist by using frequency division multiplexing and separating new DOCSIS versions from old ones according to their operation frequencies.
[src:docsis-cable/docsis] As frequency allocation bandwidth plans differ between United States and European CATV systems, DOCSIS standards earlier than 3.1 have been modified for use in Europe.
[src:docsis-cable/docsis] These modifications were published under the name **EuroDOCSIS**.
[src:docsis-cable/docsis] The differences between the bandwidths exist because European cable TV conforms to PAL/DVB-C standards of 8 MHz RF channel bandwidth and North American cable TV conforms to NTSC/ATSC standards which specify 6 MHz per channel.
[src:docsis-cable/docsis] The wider channel bandwidth in EuroDOCSIS architectures permits more bandwidth to be allocated to the downstream data path (toward the user).
[src:docsis-cable/docsis] EuroDOCSIS certification testing is executed by Belgian company Excentis (formerly known as tComLabs), while DOCSIS certification testing is executed by CableLabs.
[src:docsis-cable/docsis] Typically, customer premises equipment receives "certification", while CMTS equipment receives "qualification".
[src:docsis-cable/docsis] The ITU Telecommunication Standardization Sector (ITU-T) has approved the various versions of DOCSIS as international standards.
[src:docsis-cable/docsis] DOCSIS 1.0 was ratified as ITU-T Recommendation J.112 Annex B (1998), but it was superseded by DOCSIS 1.1 which was ratified as ITU-T Recommendation J.112 Annex B (2001).
[src:docsis-cable/docsis] Subsequently, DOCSIS 2.0 was ratified as ITU-T Recommendation J.122.
[src:docsis-cable/docsis] Note: While ITU-T Recommendation J.112 Annex B corresponds to DOCSIS/EuroDOCSIS 1.1, Annex A describes an earlier European cable modem system ("DVB EuroModem") based on ATM transmission standards.
[src:docsis-cable/docsis] Annex C describes a variant of DOCSIS 1.1 that is designed to operate in Japanese cable systems.
[src:docsis-cable/docsis] The ITU-T Recommendation J.122 main body corresponds to DOCSIS 2.0, J.122 Annex F corresponds to EuroDOCSIS 2.0, and J.122 Annex J describes the Japanese variant of DOCSIS 2.0 (analogous to Annex C of J.112).
[src:docsis-cable/docsis] DOCSIS provides a variety of options available at Open Systems Interconnection (OSI) layers 1 and 2—the physical and data link layers.
[src:docsis-cable/docsis] Bandwidth is shared among users of an HFC, within service groups which are groups of customers that share RF channels.
[src:docsis-cable/docsis] The first three versions of the DOCSIS standard support a downstream throughput with 256-QAM of up to 42.88 Mbit/s per 6 MHz channel (approximately 38 Mbit/s after overhead), or 55.62 Mbit/s per 8 MHz channel for EuroDOCSIS (approximately 50 Mbit/s after overhead).
[src:docsis-cable/docsis] The upstream throughput possible is 30.72 Mbit/s per 6.4 MHz channel (approximately 27 Mbit/s after overhead), or 10.24 Mbit/s per 3.2 MHz channel (approximately 9 Mbit/s after overhead).
[src:docsis-cable/docsis] DOCSIS 3.1 supports a downstream throughput with 4096-QAM and 25 kHz subcarrier spacing of up to 1.89 Gbit/s per 192 MHz OFDM channel.
[src:docsis-cable/docsis] The upstream throughput possible is 0.94 Gbit/s per 96 MHz OFDMA channel.
[src:docsis-cable/docsis] Tables assume 256-QAM modulation for downstream and 64-QAM for upstream on DOCSIS 3.0, and 4096-QAM modulation for OFDM/OFDMA (first downstream/upstream methods) on DOCSIS 3.1, although real-world data rates may be lower due to variable modulation depending on SNR.
[src:docsis-cable/docsis] Higher data rates are possible but require higher order QAM schemes which require higher downstream modulation error ratio (MER).
[src:docsis-cable/docsis] DOCSIS 3.1 was designed to support up to 8192-QAM/16,384-QAM, but only support of up through 4096-QAM is mandatory to meet the minimum DOCSIS 3.1 standards.
[src:docsis-cable/docsis] For DOCSIS 3.0, the theoretical maximum throughput for the number of bonded channels are listed in the table below.
[src:docsis-cable/docsis] Note that the number of channels a cable system can support is dependent on how the cable system is set up.
[src:docsis-cable/docsis] For example, the amount of available bandwidth in each direction, the width of the channels selected in the upstream direction, and hardware constraints limit the maximum amount of channels in each direction.
[src:docsis-cable/docsis] Note that the maximum downstream bandwidth on all versions of DOCSIS depends on the version of DOCSIS used and the number of upstream channels used if DOCSIS 3.0 is used, but the upstream channel widths are independent of whether DOCSIS or EuroDOCSIS is used.
[src:docsis-cable/docsis] Traditional DOCSIS upstream in North America uses the 5–42 MHz frequency range.
[src:docsis-cable/docsis] The 5–65 MHz range is used by EuroDOCSIS.
[src:docsis-cable/docsis] This is known as a "low-split" or "sub-split" design, capable of a total shared capacity of ~108 Mbit/s upstream (assuming 4 SC-QAM upstream channels) for the service group.
[src:docsis-cable/docsis] Since DOCSIS 3.0, cable operators have begun to increase the amount of bandwidth dedicated to the upstream.
[src:docsis-cable/docsis] The two most popular options for this include a "mid-split" or "high-split".
[src:docsis-cable/docsis] A mid-split increases the upstream frequency range to 5–85 MHz, supporting a total shared upstream capacity of ~450 Mbit/s (assuming 4 SC-QAM + OFDMA channels) for the service group.
[src:docsis-cable/docsis] A high-split increases the upstream frequency range to 5–204 MHz, supporting a total shared upstream capacity of ~1.5 Gbit/s (assuming 4 SC-QAM + OFDMA channels) for the service group.
[src:docsis-cable/docsis] DOCSIS 4.0 in both full-duplex (FDX) and extended spectrum DOCSIS (ESD) configurations will support upstream speeds surpassing 5 Gbit/s.
[src:docsis-cable/docsis] A DOCSIS architecture includes two primary components: a cable modem located at the customer premises, and a cable modem termination system (CMTS) located at the CATV headend.
[src:docsis-cable/docsis] The customer PC and associated peripherals are termed customer-premises equipment (CPE).
[src:docsis-cable/docsis] The CPE are connected to the cable modem, which is in turn connected through the HFC network to the CMTS.
[src:docsis-cable/docsis] The CMTS then routes traffic between the HFC and the Internet.
[src:docsis-cable/docsis] Using provisioning systems and through the CMTS, the cable operator exercises control over the cable modem's configuration.
[src:docsis-cable/docsis] DOCSIS 2.0 was also used over microwave frequencies (10 GHz) in Ireland by Digiweb, using dedicated wireless links rather than HFC network.
[src:docsis-cable/docsis] At each subscriber premises the ordinary CM is connected to an antenna box which converts to/from microwave frequencies and transmits/receives on 10 GHz.
[src:docsis-cable/docsis] Each customer has a dedicated link but the transmitter mast must be in line of sight (most sites are hilltop).
[src:docsis-cable/docsis] DOCSIS includes media access control (MAC) layer security services in its Baseline Privacy Interface specifications.
[src:docsis-cable/docsis] DOCSIS 1.0 used the initial Baseline Privacy Interface (BPI) specification.
[src:docsis-cable/docsis] BPI was later improved with the release of the Baseline Privacy Interface Plus (BPI+) specification used by DOCSIS 1.1 and 2.0.
[src:docsis-cable/docsis] Most recently, a number of enhancements to the Baseline Privacy Interface were added as part of DOCSIS 3.0, and the specification was renamed "Security" (SEC).
[src:docsis-cable/docsis] The intent of the BPI/SEC specifications is to describe MAC layer security services for DOCSIS CMTS to cable modem communications.
[src:docsis-cable/docsis] BPI/SEC is intended to prevent cable users from listening to each other.
[src:docsis-cable/docsis] It does this by encrypting data flows between the CMTS and the cable modem.
[src:docsis-cable/docsis] BPI and BPI+ use 56-bit Data Encryption Standard (DES) encryption, while SEC adds support for 128-bit Advanced Encryption Standard (AES).
[src:docsis-cable/docsis] The AES key, however, is protected only by a 1024-bit RSA key.
[src:docsis-cable/docsis] BPI/SEC is intended to allow cable service operators to refuse service to uncertified cable modems and unauthorized users.
[src:docsis-cable/docsis] Typically, the cable service operator manually adds the cable modem's MAC address to a customer's account with the cable service operator; and the network allows access only to a cable modem that can attest to that MAC address using a valid certificate issued via the PKI.
[src:docsis-cable/docsis] The earlier BPI specification (ANSI/SCTE 22-2) had limited service protection because the underlying key management protocol did not authenticate the user's cable modem.
[src:docsis-cable/fiber-to-the-x] FTTX is a generalization for several configurations of fiber deployment, arranged into two groups: FTTP/FTTH/FTTB (fiber laid all the way to the premises/home/building) and FTTC/N (fiber laid to the cabinet/node, with copper wires completing the connection).
[src:docsis-cable/fiber-to-the-x] Residential areas already served by balanced pair distribution plant call for a trade-off between cost and capacity.
[src:docsis-cable/fiber-to-the-x] The closer the fiber head, the higher the cost of construction and the higher the channel capacity.
[src:docsis-cable/fiber-to-the-x] In places not served by metallic facilities, little cost is saved by not running fiber to the home.
[src:docsis-cable/fiber-to-the-x] Fiber to the *x* is the key method used to drive **next-generation access** (**NGA**), which describes a significant upgrade to the broadband available by making a step change in speed and quality of the service.
[src:docsis-cable/fiber-to-the-x] This is typically thought of as asymmetrical with a download speed of 24 Mbit/s plus and a fast upload speed.
[src:docsis-cable/fiber-to-the-x] A similar network called a hybrid fiber-coaxial (HFC) network is used by cable television operators but is usually not synonymous with "fiber In the loop", although similar advanced services are provided by the HFC networks.
[src:docsis-cable/fiber-to-the-x] Fixed wireless and mobile wireless technologies such as Wi-Fi, WiMAX and 3GPP Long Term Evolution (LTE) are an alternative for providing Internet access.
[src:docsis-cable/fiber-to-the-x] The telecommunications industry differentiates between several distinct FTTX configurations.
[src:docsis-cable/fiber-to-the-x] To promote consistency, especially when comparing FTTH penetration rates between countries, the three FTTH Councils of Europe, North America, and Asia-Pacific agreed upon definitions for FTTH and FTTB in 2006, with an update in 2009, 2011 and another in 2015.
[src:docsis-cable/fiber-to-the-x] The FTTH Councils do not have formal definitions for FTTC and FTTN.
[src:docsis-cable/fiber-to-the-x] Fiber to the premises (FTTP) is a form of fiber-optic communication delivery in which an optical fiber is run in an optical distribution network from the central office all the way to the premises occupied by the subscriber.
[src:docsis-cable/fiber-to-the-x] The term "FTTP" has become ambiguous and may also refer to FTTC where the fiber terminates at a utility pole without reaching the premises.
[src:docsis-cable/fiber-to-the-x] An apartment building may provide an example of the distinction between FTTH and FTTB.
[src:docsis-cable/fiber-to-the-x] If a fiber is run to a panel inside each subscriber's apartment unit, it is FTTH.
[src:docsis-cable/fiber-to-the-x] If instead, the fiber goes only as far as the apartment building's shared electrical room (either only to the ground floor or to each floor), it is FTTB.
[src:docsis-cable/fiber-to-the-x] Fiber to the curb/cabinet (FTTC) is a telecommunications system based on fiber-optic cables run to a platform that serves several customers.
[src:docsis-cable/fiber-to-the-x] Each of these customers has a connection to this platform via coaxial cable or twisted pair.
[src:docsis-cable/fiber-to-the-x] Here "curb" is an abstraction and can just as easily mean a pole-mounted device or communications closet or a shed.
[src:docsis-cable/fiber-to-the-x] Typically any system terminating fiber within 300 m (1,000 ft) of the customer premises equipment would be described as FTTC.
[src:docsis-cable/fiber-to-the-x] Fiber to the node or neighborhood (FTTN), sometimes identified with and sometimes distinguished from fiber to the cabinet (FTTC), is a telecommunication architecture based on fiber-optic cables run to a cabinet serving a neighborhood.
[src:docsis-cable/fiber-to-the-x] Customers typically connect to this cabinet using traditional coaxial cable or twisted pair wiring.
[src:docsis-cable/fiber-to-the-x] The area served by the cabinet is usually less than one mile in radius and can contain several hundred customers.
[src:docsis-cable/fiber-to-the-x] FTTN allows delivery of broadband services such as high-speed internet.
[src:docsis-cable/fiber-to-the-x] High-speed communications protocols such as broadband cable access (typically DOCSIS) or some form of digital subscriber line (DSL) are used between the cabinet and the customers.
[src:docsis-cable/fiber-to-the-x] Data rates vary according to the exact protocol used and according to how close the customer is to the cabinet.
[src:docsis-cable/fiber-to-the-x] Unlike FTTP, FTTN often uses existing coaxial or twisted-pair infrastructure to provide last mile service and is thus less costly to deploy.
[src:docsis-cable/fiber-to-the-x] In the long term, however, its bandwidth potential is limited relative to implementations that bring the fiber still closer to the subscriber.
[src:docsis-cable/fiber-to-the-x] A variant of this technique for cable television providers is used in a hybrid fiber-coaxial (HFC) system.
[src:docsis-cable/fiber-to-the-x] It is sometimes given the acronym FTTLA (fiber-to-the-last-amplifier) when it replaces analog amplifiers up to the last one before the customer (or neighborhood of customers).
[src:docsis-cable/fiber-to-the-x] FTTC allows delivery of broadband services such as high-speed internet.
[src:docsis-cable/fiber-to-the-x] Usually, existing wire is used with communications protocols such as broadband cable access (typically DOCSIS) or some form of DSL connecting the curb/cabinet and the customers.
[src:docsis-cable/fiber-to-the-x] In these protocols, the data rates vary according to the exact protocol used and according to how close the customer is to the cabinet.
[src:docsis-cable/fiber-to-the-x] Where it is feasible to run new cable, both fiber and copper Ethernet are capable of connecting the "curb" with a full 100 Mbit/s or 1 Gbit/s connection.
[src:docsis-cable/fiber-to-the-x] Even using relatively cheap outdoor category 5 copper over hundreds of meters, all Ethernet protocols including power over Ethernet (PoE) are supported.
[src:docsis-cable/fiber-to-the-x] Most fixed wireless technologies rely on PoE, including Motorola Canopy, which has low-power radios capable of running on a 12 VDC power supply fed over several tens of meters of cable.
[src:docsis-cable/fiber-to-the-x] Power line networking deployments also rely on FTTC.
[src:docsis-cable/fiber-to-the-x] By avoiding new cable and its cost and liabilities, FTTC costs less to deploy.
[src:docsis-cable/fiber-to-the-x] However, it also has historically had lower bandwidth potential than FTTP.
[src:docsis-cable/fiber-to-the-x] In the United States and Canada, the largest deployment of FTTC was carried out by BellSouth Telecommunications.
[src:docsis-cable/fiber-to-the-x] With the acquisition of BellSouth by AT&T, deployment of FTTC will end.
[src:docsis-cable/fiber-to-the-x] Future deployments will be based on either FTTN or FTTP.
[src:docsis-cable/fiber-to-the-x] Existing FTTC plant may be removed and replaced with FTTP.
[src:docsis-cable/fiber-to-the-x] Verizon, meanwhile, announced in March 2010 they were winding down Verizon FiOS expansion, concentrating on completing their network in areas that already had FiOS franchises but were not deploying to new areas, suggesting that FTTH was uneconomic beyond these areas.
[src:docsis-cable/fiber-to-the-x] However, the largest 1 Gbit/s deployment in the United States, in Chattanooga, Tennessee, despite being conducted by power utility EPB, was FTTH rather than FTTC, reaching every subscriber in a 600-square-mile area.
[src:docsis-cable/fiber-to-the-x] Monthly pricing of US$350 reflected this generally high cost of deployment.
[src:docsis-cable/fiber-to-the-x] However, Chattanooga EPB has reduced the monthly pricing to US$70/month.
[src:docsis-cable/fiber-to-the-x] Historically, both telephone and cable companies avoided hybrid networks using several different modes of transport from their point of presence into customer premises.
[src:docsis-cable/fiber-to-the-x] In effect FTTC serves as a halfway measure between fixed wireless and FTTH, with special advantages for smart appliances and electric vehicles that rely on PLC use already.
[src:docsis-cable/fiber-to-the-x] Operators around the world have been rolling out high-speed Internet access networks since the mid-2000s.
[src:docsis-cable/fiber-to-the-x] Some used a network topology known as Active Ethernet Point-to-Point to deliver services from its central office directly into subscribers' homes.
[src:docsis-cable/fiber-to-the-x] Fiber termination was handled by a residential gateway provided by Advanced Digital Broadcast inside a subscriber's home to be shared with other consumer electronics (CE) devices.
[src:docsis-cable/fiber-to-the-x] Since 2007, Italian access providers Fastweb, Vodafone, and Wind participated in an initiative called Fiber for Italy, with the aim of creating a countrywide fiber-to-the-home network in Italy.
[src:docsis-cable/fiber-to-the-x] The pilot taking place in the Italian capital, Rome, has seen symmetrical bandwidth of 100 Mbit/s.
[src:docsis-cable/fiber-to-the-x] Telecom Italia, which refused to take part in the Fiber for Italy initiative, had an even more ambitious plan to bring fiber-to-the-home and fiber-to-the-business to 138 cities by 2018.
[src:docsis-cable/fiber-to-the-x] In September 2010, the European Commission published a new "Recommendation for Regulated Access to NGA Networks" along with a list of measures to promote the deployment of fast broadband and next-generation access networks.
[src:docsis-cable/fiber-to-the-x] Portugal Telecom planned to complete its fiber-to-the-home (FTTH) nationwide rollout by 2020.
[src:docsis-cable/fiber-to-the-x] The company’s telecommunications services are now operated under the MEO brand, which as of 2025 offers fiber connections with speeds of up to 10 Gbit/s, using XGS-PON technology, available in most urban areas of Portugal.
[src:docsis-cable/fiber-to-the-x] Between September 2017 and March 2019, the number of European FTTH and FTTB subscribers increased by nearly 16%.
[src:docsis-cable/fiber-to-the-x] By 2025, the total number of premises passed by FTTH and FTTB infrastructure is expected to reach 187 million throughout Europe.
[src:docsis-cable/fiber-to-the-x] Active Line Access is an evolving standard for the provision of services over FTTP networks in the United Kingdom proposed by the regulator Ofcom and developed by the Network Interoperability Consultative Committee.
[src:docsis-cable/fiber-to-the-x] Most FTTH deployments follow one of four primary architecture types: centralized split, distributed split, star architecture, or daisy-chaining.
[src:docsis-cable/fiber-to-the-x] Fiber network developers choose architectures based on a variety of factors, such as the physical geography of the local environment, number of anticipated subscribers, and labor force skill.
[src:docsis-cable/fiber-to-the-x] It is important to distinguish cable and fiber architecture, because while the cable structure can follow one type of architecture, the fibers inside can follow a completely different one.
[src:docsis-cable/fiber-to-the-x] The conceptually simplest optical distribution network architecture is direct fiber: that is, each fiber leaving the central office goes to exactly one customer.
[src:docsis-cable/fiber-to-the-x] These networks can support tremendous bandwidth, but are expensive because of both the number of individual fibers and the necessary equipment in the central office.
[src:docsis-cable/fiber-to-the-x] Direct fiber is generally favored by new entrants and competitive operators.
[src:docsis-cable/fiber-to-the-x] A benefit is that no layer 2 networking technologies are excluded, whether Passive Optical Network (**PON**), active optical network (AON), or other.
[src:docsis-cable/fiber-to-the-x] Any form of regulatory remedy is possible using this topology.
[src:docsis-cable/fiber-to-the-x] More commonly, each fiber leaving the central office is actually shared by many customers.
[src:docsis-cable/fiber-to-the-x] It is not until such a fiber gets relatively close to the customers that it is split into individual customer-specific fibers.
[src:docsis-cable/fiber-to-the-x] AONs rely on electrically powered network equipment to distribute the signal, such as a switch or router.
[src:docsis-cable/fiber-to-the-x] Normally, signals need an optical-electrical-optical transformation in the AON.
[src:docsis-cable/fiber-to-the-x] Each signal leaving the central office is directed only to the customer for whom it is intended.
[src:docsis-cable/fiber-to-the-x] Incoming signals from the customers avoid colliding at the intersection because the powered equipment there provides buffering.
[src:docsis-cable/fiber-to-the-x] Active Ethernet (a type of Ethernet in the first mile) is a common AON, which uses optical Ethernet switches to distribute the signal, incorporating the customers' premises and the central office into a large switched Ethernet network.
[src:docsis-cable/fiber-to-the-x] Ethernet in the first mile deployments follow a point to point or star network topology and are often based on Fast Ethernet speeds of up to 100 Mbit/s.
[src:docsis-cable/fiber-to-the-x] Such networks are identical to Ethernet computer networks used in businesses and academic institutions, except that their purpose is to connect homes and buildings to a central office rather than to connect computers and printers within a location.
[src:docsis-cable/fiber-to-the-x] Each switching cabinet can handle up to 1,000 customers, although 400–500 is more typical.
[src:docsis-cable/fiber-to-the-x] This neighborhood equipment performs layer 2 switching or layer 3 switching and routing, offloading full layer 3 routing to the carrier's central office.
[src:docsis-cable/fiber-to-the-x] The IEEE 802.3ah standard enables service providers to deliver up to 1000 Mbit/s, full-duplex, over one single-mode optical fiber FTTP, depending on the provider.
[src:docsis-cable/fiber-to-the-x] A Passive Optical Network (PON) is a point-to-multipoint FTTP network architecture in which unpowered optical splitters are used to enable a single optical fiber to serve up to 128 customers.
[src:docsis-cable/fiber-to-the-x] A PON reduces the fiber and central office equipment required compared with point-to-point architecture.
[src:docsis-cable/fiber-to-the-x] Because of this, and because it needs no powered splitters or other active components from the moment it leaves the ISP's facilities until it reaches the customer, many ISPs prefer this technology.
[src:docsis-cable/fiber-to-the-x] The downstream signal coming from the central office is broadcast to each customer premises sharing a fiber.
[src:docsis-cable/fiber-to-the-x] Encryption is used to prevent eavesdropping.
[src:docsis-cable/fiber-to-the-x] Upstream signals are combined using a multiple-access protocol, usually time-division multiple access (TDMA).
[src:docsis-cable/fiber-to-the-x] Point-to-Point Protocol over Ethernet (PPPoE) is a common way of delivering triple- and quad-play (voice, video, data, and mobile) services over both fiber and hybrid fiber-coaxial (HFC) networks.
[src:docsis-cable/fiber-to-the-x] Active PPPoE uses dedicated fiber from an operator's central office all the way to the subscribers' homes, while hybrid networks (often FTTN) use it to transport data via fiber to an intermediate point to ensure sufficiently high throughput speeds over last-mile copper connections.
[src:docsis-cable/fiber-to-the-x] This approach has become increasingly popular in recent years with telecoms service providers in both North America (AT&T, Telus, for example) and Europe's Fastweb, Telecom Italia, Telekom Austria and Deutsche Telekom, for example.
[src:docsis-cable/fiber-to-the-x] Google has also looked into this approach, amongst others, as a way to deliver multiple services over open-access networks in the United States.
[src:docsis-cable/fiber-to-the-x] Once on private property, the signal is typically converted into an electrical format.
[src:docsis-cable/fiber-to-the-x] The optical network terminal (ONT, an ITU-T term) or unit (ONU, an identical IEEE term) converts the optical signal into an electrical signal using thin film filter technology.
[src:docsis-cable/fiber-to-the-x] These units require electrical power for their operation, so some providers connect them to backup batteries in case of power outages to ensure emergency access to telecommunications.
[src:docsis-cable/fiber-to-the-x] The optical line terminals "range" the optical network terminals or units in order to provide TDMA time slot assignments for upstream communication.
[src:docsis-cable/fiber-to-the-x] For FTTH and for some forms of FTTB, it is common for the building's existing Ethernet, phone, and cable TV systems to connect directly to the optical network terminal or unit.
[src:docsis-cable/fiber-to-the-x] If all three systems cannot directly reach the unit, it is possible to combine signals and transport them over a common medium such as Ethernet.
[src:docsis-cable/fiber-to-the-x] Once closer to the end user, equipment such as a router or network interface controller can separate the signals and convert them into the appropriate protocol.
[src:docsis-cable/hybrid-fibre-coaxial] In a hybrid fiber–coaxial cable system, television channels are sent from the cable system's distribution facility, the headend, to local communities through optical fiber subscriber lines.
[src:docsis-cable/hybrid-fibre-coaxial] At the local community, a fiber media converter translates the signal from a light beam to radio frequency current (RF), and sends it over coaxial cable lines for distribution to subscriber residences.
[src:docsis-cable/hybrid-fibre-coaxial] The fiber optic trunk lines provide enough bandwidth to allow additional bandwidth-intensive services such as cable internet access through DOCSIS.
[src:docsis-cable/hybrid-fibre-coaxial] Bandwidth is shared among users of an HFC.
[src:docsis-cable/hybrid-fibre-coaxial] Customers are grouped into service groups, which are groups of customers that share bandwidth among each other since they use the same RF channels to communicate with the company.
[src:docsis-cable/hybrid-fibre-coaxial] The fiber optic network extends from the cable operators' master headend, sometimes to regional headends, and out to a neighborhood's hubsite, and finally to an optical to coaxial cable node which typically serves 25 to 2000 homes.
[src:docsis-cable/hybrid-fibre-coaxial] A master headend will usually have satellite dishes for reception of distant video signals as well as IP aggregation routers.
[src:docsis-cable/hybrid-fibre-coaxial] Some master headends also house telephony equipment (such as automatic telephone exchanges) for providing telecommunications services to the community.
[src:docsis-cable/hybrid-fibre-coaxial] In an HFC network telephony is provided using PacketCable.
[src:docsis-cable/hybrid-fibre-coaxial] Separate Edge QAMs can be used to provide QAM modulated video suitable for transmission in a coaxial cable network, from digital video sources.
[src:docsis-cable/hybrid-fibre-coaxial] Edge QAMs can also be connected to a CMTS to provide internet data instead of video, in a modular CMTS architecture.
[src:docsis-cable/hybrid-fibre-coaxial] CCAPs aim to replace the conventional, integrated CMTS which only provides data and Edge QAMs used for video which are separate pieces of equipment.
[src:docsis-cable/hybrid-fibre-coaxial] These platforms host several transmitters and receivers the latter of which can be used for cable internet, and can also host Erbium-Doped Fiber Amplifiers (EDFAs) to extend the reach of the optical signals in fiber optics.
[src:docsis-cable/hybrid-fibre-coaxial] Each transmitter and receiver services one optical node.
[src:docsis-cable/hybrid-fibre-coaxial] This optical transmitter converts the RF electrical signal to a downstream optically modulated signal that is sent to the nodes.
[src:docsis-cable/hybrid-fibre-coaxial] Fiber optic cables connect the headend or hub to the optical nodes in a point-to-point or star topology, or in some cases, in a protected ring topology.
[src:docsis-cable/hybrid-fibre-coaxial] Each node can be connected via its own dedicated fiber, so fiber optic cables laid outdoors in the outside plant can have several dozen to several hundred or even thousands of fibers, an extreme example being 6912 fibers.
[src:docsis-cable/hybrid-fibre-coaxial] A fiber optic node has a broadband optical receiver, which converts the downstream optically modulated signal coming from the headend or hub to an electrical signal going to the customers.
[src:docsis-cable/hybrid-fibre-coaxial] As of 2015, the downstream signal is a RF modulated signal that typically begins at 50 MHz and ranges from 550 to 1000 MHz on the upper end.
[src:docsis-cable/hybrid-fibre-coaxial] The fiber optic node also contains a reverse- or return-path transmitter that sends communication from customers back to the headend.
[src:docsis-cable/hybrid-fibre-coaxial] In North America, this reverse signal is a modulated RF ranging from 5–42 MHz while in other parts of the world, the range is 5–65 MHz.
[src:docsis-cable/hybrid-fibre-coaxial] This electrical signal is then outputted through coaxial cable to form a coaxial trunk.
[src:docsis-cable/hybrid-fibre-coaxial] The optical portion of the network provides a large amount of flexibility.
[src:docsis-cable/hybrid-fibre-coaxial] If there are not many fiber-optic cables to the node, wavelength division multiplexing can be used to combine multiple optical signals onto the same fiber.
[src:docsis-cable/hybrid-fibre-coaxial] Optical filters are used to combine and split optical wavelengths onto the single fiber.
[src:docsis-cable/hybrid-fibre-coaxial] For example, the downstream signal could be on a wavelength at 1550 nm and the return signal could be on a wavelength at 1310 nm.
[src:docsis-cable/hybrid-fibre-coaxial] The coaxial trunk portion of the network connects 25–2000 homes (500 is typical) in a tree-and-branch configuration off of the node.
[src:docsis-cable/hybrid-fibre-coaxial] Trunk coaxial cables are connected to the optical node and form a coaxial backbone to which smaller distribution cables connect.
[src:docsis-cable/hybrid-fibre-coaxial] RF amplifiers called trunk amplifiers are used at intervals in the trunk to overcome cable attenuation and passive losses of the electrical signals caused by splitting or "tapping" the coaxial cable.
[src:docsis-cable/hybrid-fibre-coaxial] Trunk cables also carry AC power which is added to the cable line at usually either 60 or 90 V by a power supply (with a lead acid backup battery inside) and a power inserter.
[src:docsis-cable/hybrid-fibre-coaxial] The power is added to the cable line so that optical nodes, trunk and distribution amplifiers do not need an individual, external power source.
[src:docsis-cable/hybrid-fibre-coaxial] The power supply might have a power meter next to it depending on local power company regulations.
[src:docsis-cable/hybrid-fibre-coaxial] From the trunk cables, smaller distribution cables are connected to a port of one of the trunk amplifiers called a bridger to carry the RF signal and the AC power down individual streets.
[src:docsis-cable/hybrid-fibre-coaxial] Usually trunk amplifiers have two output ports: one for the trunk, and another as a bridger.
[src:docsis-cable/hybrid-fibre-coaxial] Distribution amplifiers (also called system amplifiers) can be connected from a bridger port to connect several distribution cables to the trunk if more capacity is needed as they have multiple output ports.
[src:docsis-cable/hybrid-fibre-coaxial] The distribution line is then "tapped" into and used to connect the individual drops to customer homes.
[src:docsis-cable/hybrid-fibre-coaxial] These RF taps pass the RF signal and block the AC power unless there are telephony devices that need the back-up power reliability provided by the coax power system.
[src:docsis-cable/hybrid-fibre-coaxial] The tap terminates into a small coaxial drop using a standard screw type connector known as an F connector.
[src:docsis-cable/hybrid-fibre-coaxial] The drop is then connected to the house where a ground block protects the system from stray voltages.
[src:docsis-cable/hybrid-fibre-coaxial] Depending on the design of the network, the signal can then be passed through a splitter to multiple TVs or to multiple set top boxes (cable boxes) which may then be connected to a TV.
[src:docsis-cable/hybrid-fibre-coaxial] If too many splitters are used to connect multiple TVs, the signal levels will decrease, and picture quality on analog channels will decrease.
[src:docsis-cable/hybrid-fibre-coaxial] The signal in TVs past those splitters will lose quality and require the use of a "drop" or "house" amplifier to restore the signal.
[src:docsis-cable/hybrid-fibre-coaxial] Historically the trend among cable operators has been to reduce the amount of coaxial cable used in their networks to improve signal quality, which initially led to the adoption of HFC.
[src:docsis-cable/hybrid-fibre-coaxial] HFC replaced coaxial cable networks which had coaxial trunk cables originating at the headend of the network, and HFC replaced part of these trunk cables with fiber optic cables and optical nodes.
[src:docsis-cable/hybrid-fibre-coaxial] In 1953, C-COR was the first to introduce cable powering which transmits power through coaxial cables for powering cable amplifiers.
[src:docsis-cable/hybrid-fibre-coaxial] In 1965, it introduced the use of integrated circuits in amplifiers used on utility poles and in 1969 was the first to use heat fins on amplifiers.
[src:docsis-cable/hybrid-fibre-coaxial] The first amplifiers in outdoor housings with hinges and seals, for installation between utility poles hanging from messenger wires, were offered in 1965.
[src:docsis-cable/hybrid-fibre-coaxial] In around 1973, hubs began to be used in cable networks to increase signal quality as a result of network expansion, and cable operators made efforts to reduce the number of amplifiers in cascade on coaxial parts of the network from around 20 to 5.
[src:docsis-cable/hybrid-fibre-coaxial] Supertrunks made of coaxial cable with FM modulated video signals, fiber optics or microwave links were used to connect headends to hubs.
[src:docsis-cable/hybrid-fibre-coaxial] Fiber optics were first used as a supertrunk in 1976.
[src:docsis-cable/hybrid-fibre-coaxial] FM video could be also carried in fiber optics, and fiber optics eventually replaced coaxial cables in supertrunks.
[src:docsis-cable/hybrid-fibre-coaxial] Bandwidth in cable networks increased from 216 MHz to 300 MHz in the 1970s, to 400 MHz in the 1980s, to 550 MHz, 600 MHz and 750 MHz in the 1990s, and to 870 MHz in the year 2000.
[src:docsis-cable/hybrid-fibre-coaxial] Towards the end of the 1990s GaAs (Gallium Arsenide) transistors were introduced in HFC nodes and amplifiers, replacing silicon transistors which allowed an expansion of the spectrum used in HFC from 870 MHz to 1 GHz by 2006.
[src:docsis-cable/hybrid-fibre-coaxial] GaN transistors, introduced in 2008 and adopted in the 2010s allowed for another expansion to 1.2 GHz, or for expansion from 550 MHz to 750 MHz in older networks to 1 GHz without changing the spacing between amplifiers.
[src:docsis-cable/hybrid-fibre-coaxial] Remote PHY is an evolution of the HFC network that aims to reduce the use of coaxial cable in the network and improve signal quality.
[src:docsis-cable/hybrid-fibre-coaxial] In a conventional HFC network, headend equipment such as CMTSs and CCAPs are connected to the HFC network using RF interfaces which physically are coaxial cable connections and optical signals in fiber optic cables in the network are analog.
[src:docsis-cable/hybrid-fibre-coaxial] This requires more sophisticated optical nodes which can also convert signals from digital to analog performing modulation, unlike conventional optical nodes which only need to convert signals from optical to electrical.
[src:docsis-cable/hybrid-fibre-coaxial] These devices are known as Remote PHY devices (RPDs) or Remote MACPHY devices (RMDs).
[src:docsis-cable/hybrid-fibre-coaxial] RPDs come in shelf variants which can be installed in apartment buildings (MDUs, multi dwelling units) and can also be installed in optical nodes or at a small hub which distributes signals similarly to a conventional HFC network.
[src:docsis-cable/hybrid-fibre-coaxial] Alternatively Remote PHY can allow for a CMTS/CCAP to be located in a remote data center away from customers.
[src:docsis-cable/hybrid-fibre-coaxial] Remote MACPHY, besides achieving the same purpose as Remote PHY, also moves all DOCSIS protocol functionality to the optical node or the outside plant, which can reduce latency when compared to Remote PHY.
[src:docsis-cable/hybrid-fibre-coaxial] Remote CMTS/Remote CCAP builds upon this by moving all CMTS/CCAP functionality to the outside plant.
[src:docsis-cable/hybrid-fibre-coaxial] Remote PHY allows for some reuse of existing equipment such as CMTSs/CCAPs by replacing components.
[src:docsis-cable/hybrid-fibre-coaxial] Improving internet speeds for customers can be carried out by reducing the number of service groups with subscribers from 500 subscribers to no more than 128, in what is known as a n+0 architecture, with a single node and no amplifiers.
[src:docsis-cable/hybrid-fibre-coaxial] HFC networks operating at 1.8 GHz to 3 GHz have been explored with GaN transistors.
[src:docsis-cable/hybrid-fibre-coaxial] Changes in the frequency range used for upstream signals have been proposed: a mid split which uses frequencies from 5 to 85 MHz for the upstream, a high split which uses a range from 5 to 205 MHz, and an ultra high split with several options that allow for ranges of up to 5 to 684 MHz.
[src:docsis-cable/hybrid-fibre-coaxial] Full duplex (FDX) DOCSIS allows upstream and downstream signals to simultaneously occupy a single frequency range without time division multiplexing.
[src:docsis-cable/hybrid-fibre-coaxial] Cable operators have been gradually shifting to FTTP networks using PON (Passive Optical Networks).
[src:docsis-cable/hybrid-fibre-coaxial] By using frequency-division multiplexing, a HFC network may carry a variety of services, including analog TV, digital TV (SDTV or HDTV), video on demand, telephony, and internet traffic.
[src:docsis-cable/hybrid-fibre-coaxial] Services on these systems are carried on RF signals in the 5 MHz to 1000 MHz frequency band.
[src:docsis-cable/hybrid-fibre-coaxial] The HFC network is typically operated bi-directionally, meaning that signals are carried in both directions on the same network from the headend/hub office to the home, and from the home to the headend/hub office.
[src:docsis-cable/hybrid-fibre-coaxial] The *forward-path* or *downstream* signals carry information from the headend/hub office to the home, such as video content, voice and Internet traffic.
[src:docsis-cable/hybrid-fibre-coaxial] The very first HFC networks, and very old unupgraded HFC networks, are only one-way systems.
[src:docsis-cable/hybrid-fibre-coaxial] Equipment for one-way systems may use POTS or radio networks to communicate to the headend.
[src:docsis-cable/hybrid-fibre-coaxial] HFC makes two-way communication over a cable network practical because it reduces the number of amplifiers in these networks.
[src:docsis-cable/hybrid-fibre-coaxial] The *return-path* or *upstream* signals carry information from the home to the headend/hub office, such as control signals to order a movie or internet upstream traffic.
[src:docsis-cable/hybrid-fibre-coaxial] The forward-path and the return-path are carried over the same coaxial cable in both directions between the optical node and the home.
[src:docsis-cable/hybrid-fibre-coaxial] To prevent interference of signals, the frequency band is divided into two sections.
[src:docsis-cable/hybrid-fibre-coaxial] In countries that have traditionally used NTSC System M, the sections are 52–1000 MHz for forward-path signals, and 5–42 MHz for return-path signals.
[src:docsis-cable/hybrid-fibre-coaxial] Other countries use different band sizes, but are similar in that there is much more bandwidth for downstream communication than for upstream communication.
[src:docsis-cable/hybrid-fibre-coaxial] Traditionally, since video content was sent only to the home, the HFC network was structured to be *asymmetrical*: one direction has much more data-carrying capacity than the other direction.
[src:docsis-cable/hybrid-fibre-coaxial] The return path was originally used for only some control signals to order movies, etc., which required very little bandwidth.
[src:docsis-cable/hybrid-fibre-coaxial] As additional services have been added to the HFC network, such as Internet access and telephony, the return path is being utilised more.
[src:docsis-cable/hybrid-fibre-coaxial] Multi-system operators (MSOs) developed methods of sending the various services over RF signals on the fiber optic and coaxial copper cables.
[src:docsis-cable/hybrid-fibre-coaxial] The original method to transport video over the HFC network and, still the most widely used method, is by modulation of standard analog TV channels which is similar to the method used for transmission of over-the-air broadcast.
[src:docsis-cable/hybrid-fibre-coaxial] One analog TV channel occupies a 6-MHz-wide frequency band in NTSC-based systems, or an 8-MHz-wide frequency band in PAL or SECAM-based systems.
[src:docsis-cable/hybrid-fibre-coaxial] Each channel is centred on a specific frequency carrier so that there is no interference with adjacent or harmonic channels.
[src:docsis-cable/hybrid-fibre-coaxial] To be able to view a digitally modulated channel, home, or customer-premises equipment (CPE), e.g. digital televisions, computers, or set-top boxes, are required to convert the RF signals to signals that are compatible with display devices such as analog televisions or computer monitors.
[src:docsis-cable/hybrid-fibre-coaxial] The US Federal Communications Commission (FCC) has ruled that consumers can obtain a cable card from their local MSO to authorize viewing digital channels.
[src:docsis-cable/hybrid-fibre-coaxial] By using digital video compression techniques, multiple standard and high-definition TV channels can be carried on one 6 or 8 MHz frequency carrier, thus increasing the channel carrying capacity of the HFC network by 10 times or more versus an all-analog network.
[src:docsis-cable/hybrid-fibre-coaxial] Digital subscriber line (DSL) is a technology used by traditional telephone companies to deliver advanced services (high-speed data and sometimes video) over twisted pair copper telephone wires.
[src:docsis-cable/hybrid-fibre-coaxial] It typically has lower data carrying capacity than HFC networks and data speeds can be range-limited by line lengths and quality.
[src:docsis-cable/hybrid-fibre-coaxial] Satellite television competes very well with HFC networks in delivering broadcast video services.
[src:docsis-cable/hybrid-fibre-coaxial] Interactive satellite systems are less competitive in urban environments because of their large round-trip delay times, but are attractive in rural areas and other environments with insufficient or no deployed terrestrial infrastructure.
[src:docsis-cable/hybrid-fibre-coaxial] Analogous to HFC, fiber in the loop (FITL) technology is used by telephone local exchange carriers to provide advanced services to telephone customers over the plain old telephone service (POTS) local loop.
[src:docsis-cable/hybrid-fibre-coaxial] In the 2000s, telecom companies started significant deployments of fiber to the x (FTTX) such as passive optical network solutions to deliver video, data and voice to compete with cable operators.
[src:docsis-cable/hybrid-fibre-coaxial] These can be costly to deploy but they can provide large bandwidth capacity especially for data services.
[src:docsis-cable/wide-area-network] A **wide area network** (**WAN**) is a telecommunications network that extends over a large geographic area.
[src:docsis-cable/wide-area-network] Wide area networks are often established with leased telecommunication circuits.
[src:docsis-cable/wide-area-network] Businesses, as well as schools and government entities, use wide area networks to relay data to staff, students, clients, buyers and suppliers from various locations around the world.
[src:docsis-cable/wide-area-network] In essence, this mode of telecommunication allows a business to effectively carry out its daily functions regardless of location.
[src:docsis-cable/wide-area-network] Many WANs are, however, built for one particular organization and are private.
[src:docsis-cable/wide-area-network] WANs can be separated from local area networks (LANs) in that the latter refers to physically proximal networks.
[src:docsis-cable/wide-area-network] The textbook definition of a WAN is a computer network spanning regions, countries, or even the world.
[src:docsis-cable/wide-area-network] However, in terms of the application of communication protocols and concepts, it may be best to view WANs as computer networking technologies used to transmit data over long distances, and between different networks.
[src:docsis-cable/wide-area-network] WANs are used to connect LANs and other types of networks together so that users and computers in one location can communicate with users and computers in other locations.
[src:docsis-cable/wide-area-network] Many WANs are built for one particular organization and are private.
[src:docsis-cable/wide-area-network] Others, built by Internet service providers, provide connections from an organization's LAN to the Internet.
[src:docsis-cable/wide-area-network] WANs are often built using leased lines.
[src:docsis-cable/wide-area-network] At each end of the leased line, a router connects the LAN on one side with a second router within the LAN on the other.
[src:docsis-cable/wide-area-network] Because leased lines can be very expensive, instead of using leased lines, WANs can also be built using less costly circuit switching or packet switching methods.
[src:docsis-cable/wide-area-network] Network protocols, including TCP/IP, deliver transport and addressing functions.
[src:docsis-cable/wide-area-network] Protocols including Packet over SONET/SDH, Multiprotocol Label Switching (MPLS), Asynchronous Transfer Mode (ATM) and Frame Relay are often used by service providers to deliver the links that are used in WANs.
[src:docsis-cable/wide-area-network] It is also possible to build a WAN with Ethernet.
[src:docsis-cable/wide-area-network] Academic research into wide area networks can be broken down into three areas: mathematical models, network emulation, and network simulation.
[src:docsis-cable/wide-area-network] Performance improvements are sometimes delivered via wide area file services or WAN optimization.
[src:docsis-cable/wide-area-network] Of the approximately four billion addresses defined in IPv4, about 18 million addresses in three ranges are reserved for use in private networks.
[src:docsis-cable/wide-area-network] Packets addressed in these ranges are not routable on the public Internet; they are ignored by all public routers.
[src:docsis-cable/wide-area-network] Therefore, private hosts cannot directly communicate with public networks, but require network address translation at a routing gateway for this purpose.
[src:docsis-cable/wide-area-network] Additionally, encapsulated packets may be encrypted to secure their data.
[src:docsis-cable/wide-area-network] Many technologies are available for wide-area network links.
[src:docsis-cable/wide-area-network] Examples include circuit-switched telephone lines, radio wave transmission, and optical fiber.
[src:docsis-cable/wide-area-network] New developments have successively increased transmission rates.
[src:docsis-cable/wide-area-network] 1960, a 110 bit/s line was normal on the edge of the WAN, while core links of 56 or 64 kbit/s were considered fast.
[src:docsis-cable/wide-area-network] Today, households are connected to the Internet with dial-up, asymmetric digital subscriber line (ADSL), cable, WiMAX, cellular network or fiber.
[src:docsis-cable/wide-area-network] The speeds that people can currently use range from 28.8 kbit/s through a 28K modem over a telephone connection to speeds as high as 100 Gbit/s using 100 Gigabit Ethernet.
[src:docsis-cable/wide-area-network] The following communication and networking technologies have been used to implement WANs.
[src:docsis-cable/wide-area-network] AT&T conducted trials in 2017 for business use of 400-gigabit Ethernet.
[src:docsis-cable/wide-area-network] Researchers Robert Maher, Alex Alvarado, Domaniç Lavery, and Polina Bayvel of University College London were able to increase networking speeds to 1.125 terabits per second.
[src:docsis-cable/wide-area-network] Christos Santis, graduate student Scott Steger, Amnon Yariv, Martin and Eileen Summerfield developed a new laser that potentially quadruples transfer speeds with fiber optics.
